AUDIO: '[music] &gt;&gt; Hi. Welcome to another video. So, I used one sentence to turn GLM 5.2 into a complete app builder that can plan the work, write the code, and deploy the final product for you.'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'GLM 5.2 recently dropped, and I have been using it a lot. The model is absolutely bonkers. It is currently the best usable model on the design arena, which is kind of insane because it is an'

[00:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open MIT-licensed model. The performance gap between GLM 5.1 and GLM 5.2 is quite big. I have already made two videos on it, but I wanted to make a complete setup video showing how'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can use GLM 5.2 to its fullest potential. So, first of all, I have been using it with the Z AI coding plan. The coding plan is quite good. It is genuinely great value for the money, and you can use it with many of the coding'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools that you already like. One of the places where I have been using it is Verdant, which is also sponsoring today\'s video. But, this is not going to be a boring feature walk-through. I want to solve a real problem that I regularly run into and see whether this setup can'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually produce something useful. If you make content, do freelance work, or run any small business, you probably have information spread everywhere. One spreadsheet has your projects, another document has deadlines, your invoices are somewhere else, and you\'re'

[01:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mostly relying on your brain to remember who needs a reply. For me, that means video ideas, sponsor deliverables, publishing dates, payment statuses, and notes can very quickly become a mess. So, instead of paying for another project management tool that almost fits'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this workflow, I want to build my own creator sponsorship dashboard. The app should let me track every brand deal from the first email to final payment. It should show upcoming deadlines, content status, agreed pricing, invoice status, and the next action I need to'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take. Basically, I want one small internal tool that tells me what needs my attention and where the money is. This is the kind of project where Verdant makes a lot of sense. Verdant is not just a chatbox that generates a few files.'

[01:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It can plan a larger project, divide the work into tasks, run multiple coding workflows, and keep the whole thing in sync. So, let me first show you how to connect GLM 5.2. Head over to Verdin and open the settings. Verdin now works with'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'almost all kinds of third-party APIs. Here, I can configure Cloud Code to use my Z AI endpoint, enter the API key, and select GLM 5.2 as the model. Once that is saved, Verdin can use the model'

[02:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'through the Z AI coding plan. So, you get the value of GLM 5.2, but you also get Verdin\'s project management and parallel execution around it. This combination is what makes the workflow quite interesting. Now, let\'s build the'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'app. I\'m going to create a new project and give it one prompt. I will say, build me a creator sponsorship dashboard where I can track brand deals, deliverables, deadlines, deal values, invoice statuses, contacts, and follow-up actions. Use a clean dark'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'design with rounded corners and subtle green accents. Include a dashboard, a deal pipeline, a calendar, and a persistent database. Make it responsive and ready to deploy. That is a fairly large request. We are not asking for a static landing page.'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This needs a front-end actual interactions, data that persists, and multiple parts of the app that work together. When I send the prompt, Verdin first turns the idea into a plan. You can see that it understands the'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different parts of the product before it starts randomly writing code. It identifies the dashboard, the pipeline, the deal form, the data layer, and the testing that needs to happen. This is important because one of the biggest problems with AI coding tools is'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that they can be quite good at making the first screen. But once a project has multiple connected features, they start losing track of things. Here, I can review the plan and make changes before the execution begins. I am happy with this, so let\'s start it.'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, this is where Verdin gets quite good. Instead of doing every task one after another, it can run different pieces of work in parallel. One workflow can build the main dashboard, another can work on the deal pipeline and forms. A third can handle'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the data model and persistence. They are all working on the same product, but they are not waiting around for every unrelated task to finish. If you were building this with a small team, this is basically how you would divide the work between multiple developers. Of'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course, more agents do not automatically mean better code. They still need coordination, and that is where Verdant\'s manager comes in. It keeps track of the overall plan, checks the work, and makes sure the separate tasks fit together. Let\'s wait a bit. Okay,'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the first version is now ready, and this is actually quite good. The dashboard immediately shows the information that matters. I have the total value of active deals, outstanding upcoming deadlines, and tasks that need a follow-up.'

