[05:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'accent color because Verdant remembers the project context and the design preferences I already gave it. I do not need to explain the entire application again. It knows what I mean by the dashboard and it keeps the styling consistent. Let\'s send it and see. Okay,'

[06:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is much better. The information density is higher. The overdue item is impossible to miss. And the new filter gives me a very practical view of money that still needs to be collected. That small detail is'

[06:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why building your own tool can be so useful. A generic CRM might have 50 features that I do not need, but it may still hide the one thing I care about behind four menus. Here I can change the workflow around how I actually work.'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, while this refinement is happening, I can create another task for the mobile layout. I will ask a separate workflow to test the dashboard at mobile sizes and fix anything that overflows or becomes difficult to use. So, one'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'workflow is improving the desktop experience while another checks mobile responsiveness. Both tasks run at the same time and the manager keeps track of both. This is the kind of thing that can save a lot of time on a real project. If'

[06:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I wanted to take this further, I could connect more of the business workflow as well. For example, I could sync deal records with Notion, connect payments through Stripe, or push the project to GitHub, but I do not want to bolt on'

